Powerlifting Analysis on IPF Tournaments¶

Powerlifting is a strength-based sport where athletes compete by performing three compound movements: squat, bench press, and deadlift. Each of these lifts can be loaded incredibly heavy and challenge different mucsle groups. Athletes train to lift the heaviest weight out of all three events in a single day and achieve the high possible total. Powerlifting tournaments are hosted at different levels (locally, state, regionally, nationally, and internationally) and split into different divisions based on the athletes age, sex, and weight to ensure a balanced competition.

In this project we look at data for powerlifting tournaments. We will look specifically at tournaments hosted by the International Powerlifting Federation (IPF) as they are one of the largest organizations resposible for hosting quality, high-standard competitions internationally. They do this by following a technical rulebook which is enforced by all of their affiliate organizers (technical rulebook).

As with any data analysis process, we start by obtaining the data from an open data source. Once the data is obtained, we will filter to look only at data from the IPF or their affilates. This is to ensure data integrity and accuracy of the analysis. We will explore the current standings and spread of tournament data with respect to athlete's age, sex, weight and strength levels in different combinations. Afterwards we will use regression algorithms to predict athlete strength levels.

Data Collection¶

We use Python3 and libraries such as pandas, numpy, matplotlib and scikit-learn to perform our analysis and create our models.

In [2]:
import pandas as pd

The dataset we will be using comes from the Openpowerlifting Data Service. They are a community of powerlifters who scrape the internet for tournament information and append it to their database. They provide a great service to the powerlifting community by creating a permanent archive of the world's powerlifting data and providing it in convenient formats.

Acquiring the Data¶

The data can be downloaded from the OpenPowerlifting site here. On the site, we can follow the sidebar to "Bulk CSV Downloads" and select which dataset we want to use. There is a complete dataset containing information from all tournaments and another which only contains information about tournaments hosted by the IPF or its affiliates. Additionally, there is documentation for the columns of the dataset if more information is desired. For our analysis, we will use the dataset with only IPF and affiliate information.

In [3]:
data = pd.read_csv('openipf.csv', low_memory = False)

In this dataset, we will focus primarily on these columns:

  • Sex - Sex category athlete competed in
  • Event - Tells us which lifts the athlete competed in [S] - Squat, [B] - Bench, [D] - Deadlift (or some permutation of the three)
  • Age - Athlete's age in Kg
  • AgeClass - What age range they are categorized as under IPF rules
  • Division - Name of their division (based on age and body weight)
  • BodyweightKg - Athlete's weight in Kg
  • WeightClassKg - Athlete's weight class in Kg
  • Best3SquatKg, Best3BenchKg, Best3DeadliftKg - Their heaviest successful lift out of three attempts
  • TotalKg - The total of their heaviest three successful lifts (empty if one of three lifts failed). This will also be our main indicator of an athlete's strength.
  • Country - Home country of lifter
  • MeetCountry - Country the tournament is located in
  • Date

Data Cleansing¶

Now that we have our data, let's begin cleaning. Since we know our data is merged from different IPF affiliates, there will be some inconsistencies as different affiliates can split divisions by different age or weight ranges. As per the IPF technical rule book, athletes are first divided by sex, then age group, and finally weight. As these columns are all important for identifying relationships and trends between athletes, we will remove any data that has null values for columns:

  • Age
  • Sex
  • BodyWeightKg
In [5]:
data = data.dropna(subset = ['Age', 'Sex', 'BodyweightKg', 'TotalKg'])

We will also remove any rows where the athlete's age is not recorded (as 0), recorded correctly, or athlete's who didn't qualify to compete. IPF tournaments begin at age 14 so we will filter anything beneath that.

In [6]:
data = data[data['Age'] >= 14]

As the IPF does not yet host a tournament for gender-neutral individuals and there is not enough information in the dataset to determine which category these athletes competed in, they will have to be looked at as a separate category.

Next, we will remove the AgeClassKg and WeightClassKg columns from the dataset to align better with IPF standard ranges. We will also remove Divisions as they are susceptible to this as well.

In [9]:
data = data.drop('WeightClassKg', axis = 'columns')
data = data.drop('AgeClass', axis = 'columns')
data = data.drop('Division', axis = 'columns')

We now recreate these same classes using IPF standards. For males, their age class is split from

  • Open, All age groups 14 and above
  • Sub-Junior, day he reaches 14 to 18
  • Junior, day he reaches 19 to 23
  • Master I, day he reaches 40 to 49
  • Master II, day he reaches 50 to 59
  • Master III, day he reaches 60 to 69
  • Master IV, 70 and upwards

For females, similar divisions

  • Open, All age groups 14 and above
  • Sub-Junior, day he reaches 14 to 18
  • Junior, day he reaches 19 to 23
  • Master I, day he reaches 40 to 49
  • Master II, day he reaches 50 to 59
  • Master III, day he reaches 60 to 69
  • Master IV, 70 and upwards

And for Mx, we will assume the same ranges.

  • Open, All age groups 14 and above
  • Sub-Junior, day he reaches 14 to 18
  • Junior, day he reaches 19 to 23
  • Master I, day he reaches 40 to 49
  • Master II, day he reaches 50 to 59
  • Master III, day he reaches 60 to 69
  • Master IV, 70 and upwards
In [10]:
AgeClass = []
Division = []
for index, row in data.iterrows():
    if row['Age'] >= 14 and row['Age'] <= 18:
        AgeClass.append('14-18')
        Division.append('Sub-Junior')
    elif row['Age'] >= 19 and row['Age'] <= 23:
        AgeClass.append('19-23')
        Division.append('Junior')
    elif row['Age'] >= 40 and row['Age'] <= 49:
        AgeClass.append('40-49')
        Division.append('Master I')
    elif row['Age'] >= 50 and row['Age'] <= 59:
        AgeClass.append('50-59')
        Division.append('Master II')
    elif row['Age'] >= 60 and row['Age'] <= 69:
        AgeClass.append('60-69')
        Division.append('Master III')
    elif row['Age'] >= 70 and row['Age'] <= 79:
        AgeClass.append('70-79')
        Division.append('Master IV')
    else:
        AgeClass.append('Any')
        Division.append('Open')
data['AgeClass'] = AgeClass
data['Division'] = Division

Now we follow a similar procedure for creating the WeightClassKg column except there exists differences in the weight range between male and female athletes. As there is only 8 athletes under the Mx category, we will just categorize them in similar ranges as the male athletes. The value in the new WeightClassKg column will be the upper limit of the weight class. For the final class, the no upper bound class will be denoted as 1000.

WeightClassKg = []

Exploratory Analysis¶

Now that we've categorized the athlete's division by IPF standards, we can begin exploring the data. As we've seen, the IPF goes to great lengths to create balanced divisions in order for athlete's to have a fair competition. This is done by accounting for the athlete's age, weight, and sex. We are curious as to how much of an effect these factors have an on athlete's capable strength.

Graphing Strength vs. Body Weight¶

Let's look at the relationship between an athlete's bodyweight and strength. Strength will be measured through the TotalKG columns for each athlete. This is the total amount of weight an athlete moved by participating in all three lifts. We will only look at athlete's who performed in all three lifts. We know an athlete performs all three lifts if the value in 'Event' is equal to 'SBD'.

In [12]:
tempSBD = data[data['Event'] == 'SBD']

How strong is a winner?¶

Now that we've looked at the relationships between strength based on age, sex, and events, let's attempt to identify how strong an athlete must be to win a tournmanet. How much stronger an athlete has to be can be defined by comparing them to the average results of athlete's in their same age and weight group.

We must first identify the winners in our database. According to the documentation, column 'Place' records the place of the lifter in the given division at the end of the meet. We care solely about individuals who took first place so we will filter for that. We will the find the averages strength for the winners amongst their respective age and weight categories.

Let's filter for solely first place winners.

In [34]:
winners = tempSBD[tempSBD['Place'] == '1']

Now we average all winners amongst themselves.

In [35]:
grouped_winners = winners.groupby(by = ['Sex', 'AgeClass', 'WeightClassKg']).mean()

Now we look at the total average amongst all individuals

In [36]:
grouped_total = tempSBD.groupby(by = ['Sex', 'AgeClass', 'WeightClassKg']).mean()

Finally, we calculate the difference between the two groups. Say we only care about age, body weight, best lift for each event, and the total.

In [37]:
grouped_total = grouped_total[['Age', 'BodyweightKg', 'Best3SquatKg', 'Best3BenchKg', 'Best3DeadliftKg', 'TotalKg']]
grouped_winners = grouped_winners[['Age', 'BodyweightKg', 'Best3SquatKg', 'Best3BenchKg', 'Best3DeadliftKg', 'TotalKg']]
In [38]:
diff = grouped_total.compare(grouped_winners)

In this figure we plot the average strength of all male powerlifters respective to their age and weight group. Predicting Strength in Athlete's¶

Linear Regression for Athlete's¶

We have seen now that through different combinations of categories, there is a significant relationship between an athlete's bodyweight and the amount of weight they can lift. Now, we will attempt to create a regression model which attempts to predict the amount of weight an athlete can lift based on their sex, age, and body weight. This model will calculate the expected total weight.

We will filter our data to contain only the columns we care about. We will use lift_data as a start and for later models.

In [41]:
lift_data = tempSBD[['Sex', 'Age', 'BodyweightKg', 'Best3SquatKg', 'Best3BenchKg', 'Best3DeadliftKg', 'TotalKg']]

Now that we have our lift data, we check to see if we have any categorical variables which we do. For 'Sex' we have string variables 'M', 'F', and 'Mx'. This means we must one-hot encode this column. One-hot encoding is a process which turns categorical variables into individual columns for each unique value and using 1's and 0's to indicate their value. This allows our regression model to read and use the data.

In [42]:
temp_onehot = pd.get_dummies(lift_data['Sex'])
In [43]:
lift_data = lift_data.drop('Sex', axis = 1)
In [44]:
lift_data = lift_data.join(temp_onehot)

We will create athlete_data with just the athlete's sex, age, and bodyweight. The we will use the TotalKg column as our target.

In [45]:
athlete_data = lift_data[['M', 'F', 'Mx', 'Age', 'BodyweightKg']]
strength_data = lift_data[['TotalKg']]

Next, we will initialize our regression models. We will use two different models available on scikit, the k nearest neighbor model and a decision tree model.

In [46]:
neigh = KNeighborsRegressor(algorithm = 'kd_tree', n_neighbors = 5)
In [47]:
dectree = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state = 22)

In order to fit a model, we must split the data into training and test sets. This is done in order to teach the model what our expected result should look like and then validate those results with values whose results we already know.

In [48]:

y_bydectree = dectree.predict(X_test)

Now that our model has predicted the expected strength for these athletes, now what? In order to determine if our model is effective or not, we must compare it to our actual data. We use three major measurements to test for error and which ultimately tells us the effectiveness of our models. There are mean squared error (MSE), root mean squared error (RMSE), and mean absolute error (MAE).

Starting with MSE:

In [51]:
kNN_MSE = mean_squared_error(y_bykNN, y_test)
tree_MSE = mean_squared_error(y_bydectree, y_test)
if abs(kNN_MSE) < abs(tree_MSE):
    print('kNN')
    print (kNN_MSE)
else:
    print('dectree')
    print(tree_MSE)

kNN
10448.633199618404

We see that our mean squared error is rather large. This is because MSE tends to amplify errors that are greatly off versus errors that are smaller. We can get a different interpretation from our other metrics

In [52]:
kNN_RMSE = mean_squared_error(y_bykNN, y_test, squared = False)
tree_RMSE = mean_squared_error(y_bydectree, y_test, squared = False)
if abs(kNN_RMSE) < abs(tree_RMSE):
    print('kNN')
    print (kNN_RMSE)
else:
    print('dectree')
    print(tree_RMSE)

kNN
102.21855604350124

The root mean squared error does a similar calculation as the MSE except it provides it to us in a more readable form.

In [53]:
kNN_MAE = mean_absolute_error(y_bykNN, y_test)
tree_MAE = mean_absolute_error(y_bydectree, y_test)
if abs(kNN_MAE) < abs(tree_MAE):
    print('kNN')
    print (kNN_MAE)
else:
    print('dectree')
    print(tree_MAE)

kNN
79.02081041951077

The mean absolute error gives us the actual different between the prediced and actual value. This mean that on average, our prediction is about 79 kg off. This is a big difference since that is equivalent to about ~ 175 lbs. This sort of error comes from outliers in our data from athletes who are far above the population.

We see that the error for our k nearest neighbor model has a lower error value across all our metrics. We will attempt to plot our results for the regression model.

This 3d plot shows the estimated level of strength for an athlete from our k nearest neighbor model compared to the actual strength of the athlete. We are able to see along which axis the model is most off by. We see that the model tends to underestimate the strength of the athlete's in our training data.
